      "text": "In other words, when a teacher is \"evaluated\" it is often called \"an observation.\" Yet--there is a vast difference--technically speaking--between the act of \"observing\" and \"evaluating\" teaching. This is a major problem for the tenure-track, full-time temp, and the adjunct. Everyone feels like their job is on the line when it comes time to be \"observed.\" And this is a symptom of a larger problem in education. If we cannot effectively communicate to teachers how to improve, then how can we expect them to extend the same consideration to their students? How do we empower them to care when they themselves do not feel like they are cared about--that their hard work can be completely derailed and undone by one bad \"observation.\" "
